9,"display_name":"Marzipanherz"},"score":1,"post_id":44713,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1459369495,"comment_id":78031,"body":"@David Based on the comments I assume it could be an urgent real life question rather than homework. Like &#39;my brother made this blood test and is now afraid he was adopted&#39; or so... (speculating)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":1,"post_id":44713,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459378283,"comment_id":78043,"body":"Yes, he said it was. But the moderators disagreed, so I presume the question will disappear. As your answer is correct, he will already have the info. I was just thinking what else positive we might do with the situation."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/cvKKH.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19160,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19160/user5434678","reputation":193,"display_name":"user5434678"},"score":1,"post_id":44713,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459380851,"comment_id":78044,"body":"@David- Could you provide a link so I can further study?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":1,"post_id":44713,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/cvKKH.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19160,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19160/user5434678","reputation":193,"display_name":"user5434678"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1459424411,"comment_id":78064,"body":"@user5434678 You could try this on-line text: <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21257/\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21257<\/a> but you would need to use the cross-references if you were unfamiliar with the the technical terms. The trouble is that the texts tend to start with crosses between different genotypes and work out the proportion of the various genotypes in the offspring. In contrast, here we are start with the offspring phenotype. So we need to work out what genotype(s) this could have, what cross of parent genotypes could produce it, and what the corresponding parent phenotypes would be."}],"down_vote_count":2,"last_activity_date":1459292658,"creation_date":1459284374,"body":"<p>The parents of a child with 0+ have the blood group A, B or 0, but not AB. And one or both parents are positive regarding the Rhesus-Factor (+).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>There are several factors and derived systems that allow a classification into blood groups. Your example covers two: the AB0-system and the rhesus-system.<\/p>\n\n<p>The AB0-system covers four groups: A, B, AB, and 0. In other words: people either have factor A, factor B, both factors or none. People with factor A either hand this factor down to their child, or they don't. Accordingly, people with factor B either hand it down or not. People with AB in any case hand down one factor, either A or B. People without a factor (group 0) can't hand down A or B. Given those rules, a child with griup 0 did not inherit factor A nor B. So the parents of this child don't have group AB, but can have any of the other three groups.<\/p>\n\n<p>The rhesus-system is about having (being positive, +) or lacking (being negative, -) an other factor, the so called Rhesus factor. A rhesus- positive person either does or doesn't hand down this factor to his/her children. A rhesus-negative person has nothing to hand down. Thus, knowing that the child in your example is rhesus-positive, it  did inherit this factor from at least one of its parents. This,  one can assume that one or both parents also carry this factor.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Final remarks:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>There can be rare exceptions from the above mentioned rules.<\/li>\n<li>There are more details about this topic worth reading. However, I skipped them to keep the answer readable.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":44713,"question_id":44712,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1459292658}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44712/making-a-offspring-with-o-blood","last_activity_date":1459292658,"creation_date":1459281845,"answer_count":1,"title":"Making a offspring with O+ blood","body":"<p>If offspring is O+ what blood type would parents have to have to make this possible?<\/p>\n","question_id":44712,"tags":["dna","hematology","blood-group"],"score":-3,"down_vote_count":4,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":63,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"score":1,"post_id":44706,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459278511,"comment_id":77972,"body":"Thank you for your post and the additional information!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459275682,"creation_date":1459274880,"body":"<p>Unless there's a feedback mechanism shutting off gene expression (which controls the proteins made by a cell), activation or deactivation of an enzyme is not in itself a matter of gene expression, it's a matter of external factors controlling the enzyme's activity. You need to decide on what exactly causes skin pigmentation: the enzyme or cell proliferation, and what is under the control of gene expression and what isn't.<\/p>\n\n<p>Most of what you find on ultraviolet light and melanin will be somehow related to melanomas, the formation of which does involve gene expression, so it's important to keep the two separated.<\/p>\n\n<p>Ultraviolet light does cause proliferation of melanocytes, which cause the skin to darken. Melanocytes impart melanin to keratinocytes; these cells then are what give you a tan. The keratinocytes undergo constant turnover, so are eventually shed, and in the absence of continued exposure to UV radiation, there is no need to keep producing melanin-heavy keratinocytes. \n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/H6jJW.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/H6jJW.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The keratins and proteins within the stratum corneum act mainly by scattering and absorbing the UV. UV-R sets in action an integrated mechanism for the formation and delivery of melanin within melanosomes from melanocytes to keratinocytes. This mechanism is probably triggered by keratinocytes, <strong>which respond to UV-R with bursts of mitoses and with increased production of ET-1 and POMC, thus creating a new demand for melanosomes.<\/strong> The mitotic rate of basal keratinocytes increases a day after UV exposure, reaches a maximum 2 days later, and maintains this level for ∼1 wk. It then declines, and the skin regains its original thickness after 1\u20132 months if there has been no subsequent exposure.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Continued exposure to UV light stimulates the melanocytes to grow. This increases the chance of the development of melanomas. Since skin cells containing melanin are shed (there's no getting around that), in light-skinned individuals, keeping a tan is to keep injuring the skin and risking carcinogenesis.<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><a href=\"http://physrev.physiology.org/content/84/4/1155\" rel=\"nofollow\">Melanin Pigmentation in Mammalian Skin and Its Hormonal Regulation<\/a><\/sub><br>\n<sub><a href=\"http://www.fasebj.org/content/21/4/976.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">Human skin pigmentation: melanocytes modulate skin color in response to stress<\/a><\/sub><br>\n<sub><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2564815/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mechanism of UV-related carcinogenesis and its contribution to nevi/melanoma<\/a><\/sub>    <\/p>\n","answer_id":44706,"question_id":44704,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1459275682},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":44711,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459281555,"comment_id":77975,"body":"Awesome, this is exactly what I needed. If only I could select two answers. By the way, I&#39;m a visual learner, so those diagrams really helped. Thank you, Chris!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":0,"post_id":44711,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"edited":false,"creation_date":1459306107,"comment_id":77992,"body":"@AleksandrH - Please feel free to accept Chris&#39;s answer. It directly answers your question, and is frankly a lot better than my answer. +1. This kind of answer makes me appreciate how much I&#39;ve lost touch with molecular biology."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":44711,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1459332702,"comment_id":78007,"body":"@anongoodnurse Alright, thanks to both of you for your thorough answers &amp; the references :)"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459280043,"creation_date":1459280043,"body":"<p>Since @anongoodnurse already nicely covery the effects of UV radiation on the cellular level, I will only have a look on the molecular level.<\/p>\n\n<p>UV radiation of the skin causes increased DNA damage and thus activity of p53 in the keratinocytes of the skin. This causes (amongst others) the production of Kitl (Kit ligand, binds to the Kit receptor) and POMC (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proopiomelanocortin\" rel=\"nofollow\">Proopiomelanocortin<\/a>) which is later processed to ACTH (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrenocorticotropic_hormone\" rel=\"nofollow\">Adrenocorticotropic hormone<\/a>) and the different MSH-forms (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocyte-stimulating_hormone\" rel=\"nofollow\">Melanocyte-stimulating hormone<\/a>). These act on the MC1R (Melanocortin 1 receptor) on the surface of the melanocytes and induce pigmentation. See the figure below from reference 1 as illustration:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/B8LCS.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/B8LCS.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>In the melanocytes the binding of these ligands activates different signal transduction pathways which all finally lead to the activation of the transcription factor MITF (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microphthalmia-associated_transcription_factor\" rel=\"nofollow\">Microphtalmia-associated transcription factor<\/a>) which then upregulates the transcription of tyrosinase. \nSee the figure from reference 1 as an illustration about what goes on in the cell:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/8ceQE.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/8ceQE.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>So the activity of the sun directly influences the signal transduction and later on the gene expression of Tyrosinase by a specific transcription factor. This translates a external stimulus (as UV light) down to the gene expression level. The stimulus does not affect the activity of the enzyme, only the amount available.<\/p>\n\n<p>This upregulation stops when there is no further signalling down from the keratinocytes and eventually the Tyrosinase will be degraded due to normal turnover of the enzyme. Since no or only little is made without the right stimulus, this causes a stop or reduction in the pigment production. This happens when you get less UV light on your skin which happens for example in the winter time in Europe. Shedding of the upper layers of the epidermis then leads to the loss of the pigmented keratinocytes which makes persons lighter.<\/p>\n\n<p>References:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25414302\" rel=\"nofollow\">The melanoma revolution: From UV carcinogenesis to a new era in\ntherapeutics<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25111671\" rel=\"nofollow\">The roles of microphthalmia-associated transcription factor and\npigmentation in melanoma.<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":44711,"question_id":44704,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44704/is-the-increased-decreased-enzyme-activity-tyrosinase-caused-by-an-environment","last_activity_date":1459280043,"creation_date":1459271740,"answer_count":2,"title":"Is the increased/decreased enzyme activity (tyrosinase) caused by an environmental factor (UV radiation) considered to be gene expression?","body":"<p>My AP Bio assignment asks that I research the effects of UV radiation on melanin production, but the directions and questions suggest that UV radiation influences gene expression. From what I could find, such as on <a href=\"http://enhs.umn.edu/current/5103/uv/harmful.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> university site or <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8151127\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> abstract on NCBI, it seems that UV-B radiation directly affects the enzyme tyrosinase, which is responsible for producing melanin from tyrosine. So here is what I'm wondering: is our lesson wrong in stating that UV radiation affects gene expression, since it seems that it actually affects enzyme activity?<\/p>\n","question_id":44704,"tags":["gene-expression"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":44711,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":104,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44708/measuring-gross-primary-productivity-gpp-using-light-and-dark-bottle-methods","last_activity_date":1459278422,"creation_date":1459278422,"answer_count":0,"title":"Measuring Gross Primary Productivity (GPP) using Light and Dark Bottle methods: Sample Question","body":"<p>The following question is taken from my Cliffnotes AP Biology 4th edition practice exam and it deals with the light and dark method for measuring gross primary productivity.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In a classroom investigation, students filled two bottles with pond water containing only photosynthesizing organisms. They used a dissolved oxygen (DO2) sensor to measure the amount of dissolved oxygen in each bottle. One bottle was put under a light. The second bottle was wrapped with aluminum foil to block all light and was put under the same light. AFter 24 hours, pond water DO2 in the two bottles was again measured. Average values for DO2 from all students are provided in the following table.\n  <a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/YC6gW.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/YC6gW.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n  \n  <p>Calculate the gross primary productivity for the observed sample. Express your answer in mg fixed carbon/L/day to the nearest hundredth.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Okay, so I know that net primary production (NPP) is the difference between gross primary production (from photosynthesis) minus Autotrophic respiration (Ra):<\/p>\n\n<p>NPP = GPP - Ra<\/p>\n\n<p>I also understand that the light bottle is measuring NPP, because it allows for both photosynthesis and cellular respiration. The dark bottle measures Ra because it only allows for respiration. Therefore, GPP can be calculated by rearranging the formula:<\/p>\n\n<p>GPP = NPP + Ra<\/p>\n\n<p>Calculating the difference in the final and initial values for both bottles, I get the following:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Light: 0.15 mg O2 / L   &lt;-- NPP<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Dark: -0.08 mg O2 / L   &lt;-- Ra<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Next, I plugged these into the formula:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>GPP = 0.15 - 0.08 = 0.07 mg O2 / L<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Using the conversion formulas provided on the College Board's AP Bio Appendix (essentially just multiplying the mg O2 / L value by 0.374128 to get mg Carbon fixed / L), I get the following:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>0.07 mg O2 / L * 0.374128 = 0.02618896 mg C fixed / L<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>But according to my review book's solution, I was supposed to add 0.08, not subtract it. This seems a bit strange to me. Is this a mistake in the book or am I not understanding something?<\/p>\n","question_id":44708,"tags":["ecology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":79,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jdCpl.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21388/phototroph","reputation":141,"display_name":"Phototroph"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":42673,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453836107,"comment_id":73476,"body":"<a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/38856/3340\">This<\/a> is a related question but I don&#39;t think the answer there has addressed the evolutionary aspect of acid accumulation."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jdCpl.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21388/phototroph","reputation":141,"display_name":"Phototroph"},"score":0,"post_id":42673,"reply_to_user":{"profile_i