06a3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21521/shayan-kabiri","reputation":27,"display_name":"Shayan Kabiri"},"score":0,"post_id":42799,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jdCpl.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21388/phototroph","reputation":141,"display_name":"Phototroph"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1454095597,"comment_id":73727,"body":"Actually, I think  it is more a question of diversity. most of the fruits have their own preservatives, in citrus fruits case it&#39;s citric acid.in some fruits it&#39;s high sugar concentration.in some other it&#39;s vitamin C. it&#39;s a matter of diversity and the reason that other fruits went down another path is probably a matter of chance and environment and previous terms. I hope I had answered conveniently."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":42799,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jdCpl.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21388/phototroph","reputation":141,"display_name":"Phototroph"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1460289799,"comment_id":78752,"body":"@Phototroph I think by asking &quot;Then why haven&#39;t more fruits evolved this?&quot; you are making your question opinion-based. You might want to read <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/35532/why-do-some-bad-traits-evolve-and-good-ones-dont\" title=\"why do some bad traits evolve and good ones dont\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/35532/&hellip;<\/a> for help. In short, evolution is not meant to make organisms better, but just to become different from others. Its natural selection by which better ones survive while worse ones can&#39;t."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jdCpl.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21388/phototroph","reputation":141,"display_name":"Phototroph"},"score":0,"post_id":42799,"edited":false,"creation_date":1460403878,"comment_id":78863,"body":"I realise how evolution works, apologies if my wording doesn&#39;t make it clear. Haven&#39;t contributed further to this because Shayan&#39;s comment more or less answers my question (it&#39;s a question of diversity), but have left this open to see if anyone else has anything further to contribute"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1454092297,"creation_date":1454092297,"body":"<p>Actually citric acid is not only available in citrus fruit but also in pretty much any living thing. it is an important intermediate in Krebs cycle, but I guess the main reason that it is available in high concentrations in citrus fruits is because citrate is an inhibitory compound for phosphofructokinase, that means it stops the glycolysis and hence it makes it hard for bacteria to use the fructose available in the fruit body.<\/p>\n\n<p>Source:\n Stryer, Lubert; Berg, Jeremy; Tymoczko, John (2003). \"Section 16.2: The Glycolytic Pathway Is Tightly Controlled\". Biochemistry (5. ed., international ed., 3. printing ed.). New York: Freeman. ISBN 978-0716746843.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42799,"question_id":42673,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42673/why-does-citric-acid-occur-in-citrus-fruits","last_activity_date":1459278353,"creation_date":1453804550,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does Citric Acid occur in Citrus fruits?","body":"<p>Why is there so much citric acid in citrus fruits? And how did it evolve i.e. what did it come from? Is it a by-product of the ripening process?  Why have citrus fruit evolved a particularly high amount of citric acid 