rane is 100-200 angstrom thick....<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>following Menke (1960) these double lamellae are known as\n  <strong>Thylakoids<\/strong>...<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Now, unifying all these- <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>Lamellar system<\/strong> consists of <strong>uniform thylakoids<\/strong> , which sometimes are\n  stacked up like pennies , <strong>each stack being called a granum<\/strong> ( plu.\n  grana)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>&amp; this is as simple explanation as I can give of this utterly confusing Q....please feel free to comment about any portion that needs to be elaborated...<\/p>\n","answer_id":23972,"question_id":21173,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c8384ce0d304dec9dac77a67bbab4fd5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":22291,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22291/dan-beban","reputation":31,"display_name":"Dan Beban"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-uS0Elf7lRBo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAE8/R5J8cBgSOg8/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16299,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16299/vance-l-albaugh","reputation":1284,"display_name":"Vance L Albaugh"},"score":1,"post_id":43886,"edited":false,"creation_date":1456954406,"comment_id":76112,"body":"can you give some references for additional information and/or to back up your answer? It&#39;s something that we always appreciate in this community."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459273781,"creation_date":1456950141,"body":"<p>The answer above goes in depth so I will try go off that.\nFirstly, lamella is the word used to describe plate-like structures. A thylakoid therefore, being a flattened vesicle, would fit this description, so a thylakoid is a type of lamella.\nAs mentioned earlier, a lamellar system consists of uniform thylakoids, the thylakoids being the individual lamella.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have the same textbook as you, OCR A2 Biology, and I must admit I had the same confusion. What this textbook fails to mention is the fact that thylakoids are just one type of lamellae.<\/p>\n\n<p>The textbook also states that the inner membrane of the chloroplast is \"folded into lamellae (thin plates)\". There are two types of lamellae in the chloroplast, thylakoids and intergranal lamellae, both are stacked, however only thylakoids appear as \"piles of pennies\" as it states. Intergranal lamellae look nothing like pennies, which is why the textbook is strongly misleading, they are big flattened bits of membrane that connect together different grana (stacks of thylakoids).<\/p>\n\n<p>Note: my answer comes in 3 years late (I'm currently doing my A2), and the textbook in question will see its last use this year as the current A2 level syllabus is updated, I hope my answer still helps to clear up any confusion should OCR mess up again on this one<\/p>\n","answer_id":43886,"question_id":21173,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1459273781}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21173/difference-between-thylakoids-and-lamellae-in-a-chloroplast","last_activity_date":1459273781,"creation_date":1410341450,"answer_count":2,"title":"Difference between thylakoids and lamellae in a chloroplast?","body":"<p>I'm slightly confused as to the difference between thylakoids and lamellae. My understanding was that thylakoids are 'discs' that are stacked into grana and there is a membrane between the grana called the integranal lamellae. However in my text book it says that 'the inner membrane is folded into lamellae, which are stacked up like piles of pennies. Each stack of lamallae is called a granum.' This sounds to me like the description of thylakoids.\nIt later says 'grana are stacks of flattened membrane compartments, called thylakoids'...<\/p>\n\n<p>Could someone clarify this?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you in advance :)<\/p>\n","question_id":21173,"tags":["botany","plant-anatomy","chloroplasts"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1741,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1410374153},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/638a1f0df85c2f834c85d68a6b78764f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8196,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8196/user3683367","reputation":45,"display_name":"user3683367","accept_rate":50},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1426598509,"creation_date":1426594025,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nMyopic eyes can still focus on nearby images as the lens needs to relax a bit more than in a normally-sighted person. However, objects far away cannot be focused, because in a complete relaxed state (for distant objects), the lens focuses the image in front of the retina. Hyperopic eyes cannot focus on nearby objects as, at a certain close distance, the lens reaches maximum accomodation (maximum roundness) and objects cannot be focused any longer. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\n<em>Myopia<\/em> or near-sightedness is a condition of the eye where the light that comes in does not directly focus on the retina but in front of it, causing the image that one sees when looking at a distant object to be out of focus, but in focus when looking at a close object. Often the eye ball is too long, or the cornea has too much curvature (<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/eye-health/nearsightedness-myopia\" rel=\"nofollow\">Web MD<\/a>).  <\/p>\n\n<p><em>Hyperopia<\/em> (\"over-measured sight\") or farsightedness, is a defect of vision caused typically by the eyeball being too short, or a lens that cannot accomodate/become round enough. It causes difficulty focusing on near objects (<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperopia\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/PuGHw.jpg\" alt=\"Far and nearsightedness\"><br>\n<sup>Source:<a href=\"http://www.monroepublishing.com/feature/kidshealth/sight3.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Monroe Publishing<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n","answer_id":30506,"question_id":30504,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1426598509}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30504/what-is-the-difference-between-myopia-and-hyperopia","last_activity_date":1459268563,"creation_date":1426591409,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the difference between myopia and hyperopia?","body":"<p>In <em>myopia<\/em> the lens is bending the light too much even in the most relaxed state. Thus the image is produced in front of the retina. If the object comes closer  the lens just adjusts a bit less than a healthy eye and the myopic subject is able to see clearly.<\/p>\n\n<p>Why is the <em>hyperopic<\/em> eye not able to do that? If the object is far away, could the lens not just bend a bit more to elicit normal vision? So, why is the Myopic eye able to adjust its focus, but the Hyperopic not?<\/p>\n","question_id":30504,"tags":["vision","human-eye"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":30506,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1040,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1427028875},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/278d9daf6f6943cdff34fe370c41788e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21595,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21595/marijn","reputation":624,"display_name":"Marijn ","accept_rate":0},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459267269,"creation_date":1459267269,"body":"<p>Sunburn causes damages in the skin which further triggers an immune reaction.\nThis immune reaction causes a dilation of the capillaries in the skin to allow a higher transport rate towards the inflammation site. This dilation and the higher blood flow in the area causes the \"redness\" of inflamed tissues. See the image for illustration (from <a href=\"http://www.skintots.com/sunburn/what-is-sunburn-pictures-causes-rash-swelling-prevent/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>):<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/pIRP7.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/pIRP7.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The delay in the appearance (for more severe cases also the swelling) is caused by the time it takes for the body to react and to develop an immune response. For further information you can look <a href=\"http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/what-happens-when-you-get/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.thenakedscientists.com/HTML/questions/question/1830/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":44702,"question_id":44701,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44701/if-our-skin-is-burned-by-the-sun-what-causes-the-red-color-of-the-skin","last_activity_date":1459267315,"creation_date":1459265579,"answer_count":1,"title":"If our skin is burned by the sun what causes the red color of the skin?","body":"<p>Mostly it is not a good sign we are burned because too much UV light has damaged our skin and increases skincancers. <\/p>\n\n<p>But the red color we get after a few ours, what is the exact cause of it and why is it red? Is that our blood we see or other changes in skincells or our immunesystem reacting?<\/p>\n\n<p>And why does it takes a while before it gets red?<\/p>\n","question_id":44701,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":53,"up_vote_count"