iology.stackexchange.com/users/22452/ajitanshu-singh","reputation":182,"display_name":"ajitanshu singh"},"score":1,"post_id":44675,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459187970,"comment_id":77924,"body":"Regarding your 1st question (in the list) you should know that in exothermic reactions, energy is released by the breaking of bonds. Therefore, all the energy that ATP has is stored in its bonds, the breakage of which releases energy required by that particular organelle. For more clarity, energy of ATP is bond energy."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-xB1pHtVN6TQ/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAaY/Oc9_Qp5zq-A/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":22452,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22452/ajitanshu-singh","reputation":182,"display_name":"ajitanshu singh"},"score":0,"post_id":44675,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459188446,"comment_id":77925,"body":"Obviously, ATP is used by cell so that it can function, ever thought why you need food? :D"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-xB1pHtVN6TQ/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAaY/Oc9_Qp5zq-A/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":22452,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22452/ajitanshu-singh","reputation":182,"display_name":"ajitanshu singh"},"score":0,"post_id":44675,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459188570,"comment_id":77928,"body":"ATP transport is commonly by active transport."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":0,"post_id":44675,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459197691,"comment_id":77937,"body":"Too many questions! You need to go away and read a biochemistry text book, then come back when you have questions about particular points you don&#39;t understand. And you also might find out what organelles are and what they do. The mitochondrion for one generates energy, rather than uses it."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b62f68f2f334d828423b8706fc88c56e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16433,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16433/r-m","reputation":655,"display_name":"R.M."},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459196140,"creation_date":1459196140,"body":"<p>\"Energy\" is the ability to do work. We say that a rock perched on a cliff has potential energy, because if it falls it can do work. (Say by crushing a car that's parked underneath it.) When you look at a balanced rock, you can't see any of that potential energy - the rock on a cliff looks like the one in the valley. The one on the cliff only has energy within it because it \"wants\" to fall, and by doing so will cause other things to change.<\/p>\n\n<p>Likewise with ATP. There really isn't anything about the ATP molecule where you can \"see\" the energy. The reason the ATP molecule has energy is because it \"wants\" to break up into ADP and phosphate. Like the rock on the cliff, ATP is in a meta-stable state. It's okay for right now, but give it a nudge and it will crush your car ... er, power your organelles. -- That's what enzymes using ATP do. They attach a bunch of ropes and pulleys to the ATP boulder, then push it off the cliff. ATP drops down, becoming ADP and phosphate, but as it does so the enzyme uses the ropes and pulleys to lift something else up.<\/p>\n\n<p>And what that energy does ... well, it does practically everything. In order for the cell to function, it needs to take low energy raw material and transform it into higher energy material. It needs to take amino acids and stick them together into (higher energy) proteins. It needs to synthesize (high energy) lipids for the cell membrane. It needs to use energy to transport cargo from over here to over there. It needs to transport various substances across the membrane. (These later two are using energy to overcome entropy.) All of these events need energy, and various enzymes use ATP to do it, by arranging things such that when ATP drops to ADP and phosphate the other end of the \"rope\" (the amino acids, the lipids, the transported goods) are raised up in energy.<\/p>\n\n<p>As far as how ATP gets where it's needed, that depends. In the cytoplasm, there's a pool of available ATP, and it's free to diffuse. So an enzyme in the cytoplasm just grabs an ATP that's lying nearby, and over time a new ATP will float past it. However, there are various barriers in the cell, like the membrane of the mitochondria. In order to get past those, the ATP needs to be transported. Passive transport (basically a gate that lets ATP flow through) is a possibility, but for things like the mitochondrial membrane that's too slow, so the cell has active transport. These are little enzyme pumps that sit in the membrane and pull ATP from inside the mitochondria to the outside. (In the mitochondria this is fueled by the same hydrogen ion gradient that helps fuel ATP synthesis.)<\/p>\n","answer_id":44681,"question_id":44675,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44675/how-exactly-do-we-get-energy-from-food","last_activity_date":1459196140,"creation_date":1459187384,"answer_count":1,"title":"How exactly do we get \"energy\" from food?","body":"<p>I am captivated by human biology and I'm currently trying to understand the body and its processes in a greater depth. Thank you so much for your time and consideration! :-D I'm sorry for the rambling that follows. I included it hopefully for someone to note what I am failing to understand.<\/p>\n\n<p>So I'm currently trying to understand how it is that we get \"energy\" from food. I'm trying to fill in the gaps of my understanding.<\/p>\n\n<p>It's our cells that get the energy, right? I am well aware of how food is digested and that through cellular respiration our body takes glucose and makes ATP. Then I know that the energy is stored in unstable bonds of ATP. It's what follows that I am unaware of.<\/p>\n\n<p>Right now, I believe that the ATP is \"delivered\" to particular cell's organelles that need energy. Is that true? If so, how does that happen? I imagine that it's not that an organelle \"requests\" energy and it is delivered as much as there is a somewhat random symphony of an organelle needing energy and ATP happening to be in close proximity. Is that how it actually is in the cell?<\/p>\n\n<p>Moreover, what is the \"energy\" in an ATP molecule is and how is that energy used by an organelle?<\/p>\n\n<p>Hopefully this rambling demonstrates what I'd like to understand, but currently don't. Maybe this a tidier list of my questions:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What is the \"energy\" we refer to in an ATP?<\/li>\n<li>What does that energy do in a cell (i.e., does an organelle use that energy to function)?<\/li>\n<li>How does ATP go where it's needed?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":44675,"tags":["cell-biology","physiology","digestive-system","cellular-respiration","energy"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"too broad","is_answered":false,"view_count":30,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/UWUI3.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22821/timureke","reputation":28,"display_name":"TimurEke"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/04e6ee2e426f6de74b6d5c4ec3833bc2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22357,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22357/maljam","reputation":387,"display_name":"Maljam"},"score":1,"post_id":44678,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459188471,"comment_id":77927,"body":"Simply because silicon-based computers fundamentally work with and store information in binary. So even if we wanted to think of the data in base-4, the computer would still have to convert to binary"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/UWUI3.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22821/timureke","reputation":28,"display_name":"TimurEke"},"score":0,"post_id":44678,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/04e6ee2e426f6de74b6d5c4ec3833bc2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22357,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22357/maljam","reputation":387,"display_name":"Maljam"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1459193890,"comment_id":77936,"body":"But DNA, as a storage device is base4, so the binary computer should encode the information to base4 to use the whole potential of the storage device."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b62f68f2f334d828423b8706fc88c56e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16433,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16433/r-m","reputation":655,"display_name":"R.M."},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":1,"post_id":44680,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459253523,"comment_id":77966,"body":"Interesting. When I first read the question I wrongly assumed that they had just used two bases in the synthetic DNA, and I wondered if they had avoided C because of its spontaneous deamination to U. This might seem better for long term storage. Wonder why they didn&#39;t do that. Presumably something structural."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459194629,"creation_date":1459194629,"body":"<p>In the <a href=\"http://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2012/08/15/science.1226355\">research article<\/a> on the effort, they give the following explanation for doubling up nucleotides, rather than have each nucleotide stand for two bits:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>This allows us to encode messages many ways in order to avoid sequences that are difficult to read or write such as extreme GC <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>In practice, they chose which base of the pair it was randomly (so a 50% GC content), while disallowing homopolymer runs greater than three.<\/p>\n\n<p>Their scheme also uses barcodes and addresses as the \"table of contents\"/\"index\"/\"page numbers\". (The data wasn't stored on a single long piece of DNA, but on a large number of shorter fragments.) By having a slightly flexible coding scheme, this allows them to potentially avoid inserting those annotation elements within the contents. <\/p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, a slightly flexible coding scheme would allow them to avoid accidentally encoding a text with part of a select agent's genome. (That is, you wouldn't want to synthesize part of the smallpox genome when you're storing your novel. If you can change the nucleotides used, you can avoid that.)<\/p>\n","answer_id":44680,"question_id":44678,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44678/why-do-we-encode-information-in-dna-in-binary-and-not-in-base-4","last_activity_date":1459194629,"creation_date":1459188370,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do we encode information in DNA in binary and not in base 4?","body":"<p>I recently read an article about Harvard scientists encoding 700Tb of data in DNA strands. But they encoded the information in base 2, so T and G was a 1 and C and A was a 0. But why binary? Why didn't they just use base 4? It would be much more efficient!<\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT: here the <a href=\"http://hms.harvard.edu/news/writing-book-dna-8-16-12\">link<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":44678,"tags":["dna","bioinformatics","dna-sequencing"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":44680,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":84,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1459188899},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uonSZ.