00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":44635,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459022067,"comment_id":77852,"body":"I also think, that the copper is much less of a problem than a deep wound by such a weapon."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459018974,"creation_date":1459018974,"body":"<p>Excess copper in the body <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copper_toxicity\" rel=\"nofollow\">can be toxic<\/a> but I'm not sure a copper blade would be especially toxic unless it was coated with something else or it remained in the wound. Copper can be acutely toxic when ingested, or chronically over a long period of exposure (like lead), but is more often associated with a failure in copper excretion. Since the body has <a href=\"http://m.physrev.physiology.org/content/87/3/1011.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">ways of dealing with excess copper<\/a>, I just don't see much merit in the super-toxic copper blade, unless it is designed to break off in the target. <\/p>\n","answer_id":44635,"question_id":44533,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44533/does-copper-exacerbate-wounds","last_activity_date":1459057507,"creation_date":1458699715,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does copper exacerbate wounds?","body":"<p>There is a three edged stiletto (weapon, not shoe) with a triangular cross-section that is often touted as being \"extra dangerous\" because of the triangular puncture it makes, and its copper construction. The claim is that the copper inclusion causes something colloquially referred to as \"blood poisoning.\"<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any basis to the idea that a copper blade would cause some kind of secondary toxic effect?<\/p>\n","question_id":44533,"tags":["molecular-biology","toxicology","injury","poison"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":54,"up_vote_cou