e":"ajitanshu singh"},"score":1,"post_id":40056,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459147378,"comment_id":77896,"body":"Another reason that oxygen is not stored could be that it would result in Warburg effect i.e, reduction in photosynthesis due to decreased functioning of RUBisCO due to increased O2 conc. and also due to photooxidation of chlorophyll due to same reasons."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459025976,"creation_date":1446123513,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nPlants release O<sub>2<\/sub>, because it is not an energy source. Instead, it is used to free energy from energy-rich organic compounds. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\nPlants are solar powered. They release oxygen as a waste product during carbon fixation. Carbon fixation is basically the storage of solar power into carbon-bonds in glucose, a process referred to as <a href=\"http://chemwiki.ucdavis.edu/Biological_Chemistry/Metabolism/Electron_Transport_Chain\" rel=\"nofollow\">photosynthesis or the <strong>Calvin Cycle<\/strong><\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>To release the solar energy from glucose it has to be burned (oxidized). Oxidation of glucose can be realized via the the <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21163/\" rel=\"nofollow\">citric acid cycle (or <strong>Krebs cycle<\/strong>)<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK22505/\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>electron transport chain<\/strong><\/a> to generate ATP. O<sub>2<\/sub> only comes in in the very last step by acting as the final electron acceptor to produce H<sub>2<\/sub>O (Fig. 1.) <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/UxNgQ.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/UxNgQ.png\" alt=\"ETC\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 1. Electron transport chain in mitochondria. Electrons are sent through a chain of proteins that drive hydrogen transport out of the mitochondrial space. ATP-synthase uses the proton gradient to generate ATP. Source: <a href=\"http://chemwiki.ucdavis.edu/Biological_Chemistry/Metabolism/Electron_Transport_Chain\" rel=\"nofollow\">Davis University College<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p>Hence, O<sub>2<\/sub> is not the source of energy, it is merely used to free it from energy rich compounds such as glucose. Because it is so abundant in the atmosphere, it doesn't make sense to store it.<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21163/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Berg <em>et al<\/em>., Biochemistry. 5<sup>th<\/sup> edition. New York: W H Freeman (2002)<\/a><\/sub> <\/p>\n","answer_id":40056,"question_id":40055,"up_vote_count":11,"last_edit_date":1459025976}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40055/if-oxygen-is-such-a-good-energy-source-why-do-plants-release-it","last_activity_date":1459025976,"creation_date":1446121374,"answer_count":1,"title":"If oxygen is such a good energy source, why do plants release it?","body":"<p>Why do plants release excess oxygen, rather than consuming it entirely given it is an excellent energy source?<\/p>\n","question_id":40055,"tags":["evolution","botany","energy"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1113,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1446158989},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a63711cf89bc3fa4f3893d0e48103e99?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22542,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22542/civy","reputation":33,"display_name":"civy"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":44629,"edited":false,"creation_date":1458999603,"comment_id":77840,"body":"Have you read <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cis-Regulatory_element\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cis-Regulatory_element<\/a> and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNase_I_hypersensitive_site\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNase_I_hypersensitive_site<\/a> ?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1459000536,"creation_date":1459000235,"body":"<p><em>Cis<\/em>-regulatory elements are simply DNA regions upstream or downstream of a gene that can affect its expression (basically they have to be in the same chromosome).<\/p>\n\n<p>DNAse-I hypersensitive sites (DHS) are regions of chromatin that get digested during the DNAse treatment because they are exposed i.e. not protected by a protein (complex). The protein complex can either be a nucleosome or a transcription factor. It should be noted that a DNA region can be DNAse insensitive also because of its conformation.<\/p>\n\n<p>Usually the <em>cis<\/em>-regulatory elements exert their effects by serving as a binding site for a transcription factors (or chromatin remodellers). If the proteins bind at these sites then these regions would be protected from DNAse digestion thereby making them <em>not<\/em>-DHS. However, it is known that DNA elements can act in <em>trans<\/em> as well (see papers on 3C- <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromosome_conformation_capture\" rel=\"nofollow\">chromosome conformation capture<\/a>, and its variants). Moreover, whether a site is protected from DNAse or not does not tell anything about its function. <\/p>\n","answer_id":44632,"question_id":44629,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1459000536}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44629/whats-the-difference-between-cres-and-dhss","last_activity_date":1459000536,"creation_date":1458983651,"answer_count":1,"title":"What's the difference between CREs and DHSs?","body":"<p>I would like to know what's the difference between cis-regulating elements and DNase I\u2013hypersensitive sites, in order to produce a meaningful segregation of non coding elements affecting gene expression.<\/p>\n","question_id":44629,"tags":["gene-expression","rna","human-genome","histone","splicing"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":44632,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":25,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"score":0,"post_id":44621,"edited":false,"creation_date":1458960099,"comment_id":77820,"body":"Thanks! Those are great links. What I&#39;d have loved to find was a study of the sort where someone had taken a bunch of enzymes, immobilized them and reported on the change in activities."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"score":0,"post_id":44621,"edited":false,"creation_date":1458960359,"comment_id":77821,"body":"This snippet from your link is sort of what I wanted: &quot;As expected, after an immobilization process, the apparent Km and Vmax values are significantly affected. In literature, for example, the Vmax value for immobilized laccase compared to that of the free enzyme is reduced of about 2\u20135 times compared to the free enzyme, due to substrate diffusion to the catalytic site, with an increase of Km value. The increase of Km can be explained as a result of diffusional limitation of the substrate or to conformational changes of the enzyme resulting in a lower affinity of the substrate for the enzyme&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":1,"post_id":44621,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"edited":false,"creation_date":1458979853,"comment_id":77826,"body":"Glad the links were of use. I&#39;ll flesh out my answer on the basis of your comment to improve it."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"score":0,"post_id":44621,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459050058,"comment_id":77858,"body":"Yes! That would be very useful! Thanks."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"sco