logy.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1447848874,"creation_date":1447848874,"body":"<p>I think you are after the <strong>slope<\/strong> of the dose-response curve:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/esO2I.gif\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/esO2I.gif\" alt=\"DR curve\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Dose-response curve. Souce: <a href=\"http://www.msdmanuals.com/en-au/professional/clinical-pharmacology/pharmacodynamics/dose-response-relationships\" rel=\"nofollow\">Merck<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p>The slope indicates the <a href=\"http://www.msdmanuals.com/en-au/professional/clinical-pharmacology/pharmacodynamics/dose-response-relationships\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>change in response per unit dose<\/strong><\/a>, which translates to sensitivity.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":40752,"question_id":40730,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40730/how-to-determine-sensitivity-in-a-dose-response-curve","last_activity_date":1458986761,"creation_date":1447781856,"answer_count":1,"title":"How to determine sensitivity in a dose-response curve?","body":"<p>In a dose-response curve the % inhibition can be plotted against concentration antagonist. In our case, the effect of the antagonist is tested in different genetic variants of a microbe.<\/p>\n\n<p>When trying to determine the potency of a drug on the different variants, I compared the IC50 values. The lower the concentration required for 50% inhibition, the more potent the drug.<\/p>\n\n<p>When comparing drug efficacy, I compare the concentrations required to reach E<sub>max<\/sub> or the maximum inhibition that each drug can exert - which turns out to be 100% inhibition.<\/p>\n\n<p>To compare sensitivity, how does one proceed? <\/p>\n","question_id":40730,"tags":["pharmacology","pharmacokinetics"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answere