e,"creation_date":1438723152,"comment_id":61023,"body":"Good answer, gonna keep this open for a couple more but I like this"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/bczpO.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8952,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8952/comprehensible","reputation":186,"display_name":"comprehensible"},"score":4,"post_id":36624,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438762352,"comment_id":61055,"body":"No addictive products produced by plants can be found to have exclusively detrimental effects on the plant, they all have mostly positive effects, and plants can minimize or maximize a single chemical at their disposal, over some dozens of generations, because it&#39;s only a single chemical. Chemical changes are the most usefual and evolutionarily cheap method for plants to ward off or attract animals, easier to adjust than color, shape, hairiness, stinging cells, size, and so on."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/eboMO.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":2999,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2999/jzx","reputation":1314,"display_name":"jzx"},"score":1,"post_id":36624,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438762732,"comment_id":61056,"body":"Indeed. Even if they are generally toxic to the plant&#39;s system, they simply store them in vacuoles."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/DwwXh.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17154,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17154/lorless","reputation":101,"display_name":"lorless"},"score":7,"post_id":36624,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438858392,"comment_id":61172,"body":"+ 1 for &quot;Although, you would be hard pressed to find a better way to guarantee reproduction than being addictive to humans.&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/71d8d3c844a9033a1c70daaaff2c4ab5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.