t it"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":43664,"edited":false,"creation_date":1456452747,"comment_id":75678,"body":"If you open the question up to general databases it becomes far too broad to answer in any meaningful way. I would suggest you edit the question to make it clear what you want to know. I&#39;ve updated my answer with a bit of information relating to some of the most popular databases."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1458752372,"creation_date":1456409870,"body":"<h1>Common biology ID codes.<\/h1>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>PDB:<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.rcsb.org/pdb/explore.do?structureId=2BIB\" rel=\"nofollow\">2BIB<\/a> for example. 4 letter code for a specific structure.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><strong>Uniprot:<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q9NZT1\" rel=\"nofollow\">Q9NZT1<\/a> for example. A six letter combination of numbers and letters for either a TrEMBL or Swissprot record. This record contains information on domains, and Uniprot links out to lots of useful things like interaction databases, redundancy datasets etc.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><strong>Pfam:<\/strong> <a href=\"http://pfam.xfam.org/protein/X1WG39_DANRE\" rel=\"nofollow\">X1WG39_DANRE<\/a> A uniprot ID followed by an identifier. Tightly linked with Uniprot, but with an emphasis on domains.  <\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><strong>NCBI:<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/4557553\" rel=\"nofollow\">NP_000108.1<\/a> For example. These IDs link to either a gene, transcript or protein in refseq. In an NCBI record there are two main distinctions in prefix of the ID code: hypothetical/automatic assertions (XM_, XR_, and XP_) and manually curated assertions (NM_, NR_, and NP_). This is followed by a 6 digit number, and sometimes followed by a \".\" and a number, indicating an splice isoform.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h1>Uniprot IDs<\/h1>\n\n<p>I'm not sure where you got this output so this seems a strange concatenation of Uniprot information.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q9NZT1\" rel=\"nofollow\">Q9NZT1<\/a> is indeed the unique Uniprot ID. This is specific to uniprot.<\/p>\n\n<p>CALL5_HUMAN is the \"gene name\" or \"Identifier\" and often spans across different databases for that gene. It's a little more back end, but is essentially not unique due to splice isoforms.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are many IDs in uniprot, and many types. Already below you'll notice some are swiss prot, others are Trembl. These are the main types. Swissprot are manually reviewed, whereas Trembl is an automatically compiled collection.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/E28zJ.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/E28zJ.png\" alt=\"screenshot showing that there are half a million Swiss-prot IDs and 60 million TrEMBL IDs\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>There are many many different accession code types with each database using it's own nomenclature that you'll come across. Unfortunately, there are too many to list here comprehensively.<\/p>\n","answer_id":43670,"question_id":43664,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1458752372}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43664/understanding-common-identifier-codes-ids-in-biology-databases","last_activity_date":1458752465,"creation_date":1456405133,"answer_count":1,"title":"Understanding common identifier codes (IDs) in biology databases","body":"<p>I know this is very basic but I would like to understand it and it's difficult to know where to begin with a new database. <\/p>\n\n<p>I have the output:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>sp|Q9NZT1|CALL5_HUMAN\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>However I'm not sure exactly what this is referring to.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Is Q9NZT1 q unique identifier?<\/li>\n<li>Is CALL5_HUMAN unique too?<\/li>\n<li><p>Should one use both together to get information?<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>How many types of ID are there?<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":43664,"tags":["bioinformatics","homework","database"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":43670,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":60,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1458752465},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c2683f5b61583fcb76037b200aaeaa99?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22734,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22734/user22734","reputation":11,"display_name":"user22734"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44564/stable-isotope-sample-preparation-bone-collagen","last_activity_date":1458752418,"creation_date":1458752418,"answer_count":0,"title":"Stable isotope sample preparation: Bone Collagen","body":"<p>I am performing research in which I need to extract bone collagen from the foot bones of American Beaver (<em>Castor canadensis<\/em>).  I have read through the literature fairly thoroughly on both the archaeological/anthropological side and the wild life side and have been finding a many tweaks to a fairly simple extraction process, but I still have a few questions.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>When processing bone I split the bone and removed the center, which was red/ light pink, (I thought it was the marrow and wanted to make sure that I was getting collagen from only 1 part of the bone to not confuse my isotope data with varying tissues)<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>There is also some variability across papers in the time that people allow bone to demineralize in a strong acid  ranging from 20 mins to upwards of 10 hours.  Does anyone have any experience with this and size to which you ground your samples.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>The literature has a variety of temps ranging from 58 C to 95C, it proposes to gellatinize the collagen in a weak acid over a variable number of hours (approx pH of 3), does anyone who has experience offer a temp and time that worked for them.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Any help is much appreciated, Thanks<\/p>\n","question_id":44564,"tags":["ecology","lab-techniques","bone-biology","methods"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":10,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/df3988279c7cc61f592e90ae58dc919a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22712,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22712/qroid","reputation":23,"display_name":"Qroid"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":44530,"edited":false,"creation_date":1458692826,"comment_id":77606,"body":"Hi and welcome to Biology.SE. Without a clear scientific question to answer there isn&#39;t enough information here to answer the question."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/df3988279c7cc61f592e90ae58dc919a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22712,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22712/qroid","reputation":23,"display_name":"Qroid"},"score":0,"post_id":44530,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1458696203,"comment_id":77